s nothing at all that can be talked about adequately, and the whole art of poetry is to say what can't be said.\n\n- Alan\n|\nIt becomes an energy, when two similar souls, combine together\n\n- Rajasaraswathii, Success-Talks : For Evolution of Your Success\n|\nWalk on with hope in your heart, and you'll never walk alone\n\n- Shah\n|\nif a book isn't self-explanatory, then it isn't worth reading.\n\n- Paulo Coelho, The Zahir\n|\nYes, the stories are dangerous, she was right. A book is a magic carpet that flies you off elsewhere. A book is a door. You open it. You step through. Do you come back?\n\n- Jeanette Winterson, Why Be Happy When You Could Be Normal?\n|\nWhen there is a tendency to compartmentalize the spiritual and make it resident in a certain type of life only, the spiritual is apt gradually to be lost.\n\n- Flannery O'Connor, Mystery and Manners: Occasional Prose\n|\nBicyclist's Philosophy of Life...'It's a matter of faith. You can keep upright only by moving forward. You have to have your eyes on the goal, not the ground.\n\n- Susan\n|\nWe cannot prevail by our own might or strength, we need to plug on to the source of our strength so that we will remain resourceful always.\n\n- Jaachynma N.E. Agu, The Prince and the Pauper\n|\nAs an experienced editor, I disapprove of flashbacks, foreshadowings, and tricksy devices; they belong in the 1980s with M.A.s in postmodernism and chaos theory.\n\n- David Mitchell, Cloud Atlas\n|\nWhatever your passion, make sure you hold unto a philosophy that is bigger and greater than you.\n\n- Sunday Adelaja, The Mountain of Ignorance\n|\nThere is only One holy Knowledge, the excellent knowledge of God.\n\n- Lailah\n|\nWisdom is not in having resources, it's in knowing how to use them, when to use them & if to use them.\n\n- TemitOpe\n|\nNobody knows, nobody can ever know, not even in memory, because there are moments in time that are not knowable.\n\n- Amitav Ghosh, The Shadow Lines\n|\nIt's exhausting, the energy it takes to unknow a truth.\n\n- Chuck Palahniuk, Doomed\n|\nThis isn't life in the fast lane, it's life in the oncoming traffic.\n\n- Terry\n|\nIt's my attempt to remain invisible, not distract the reader from the story with obvious writing.\n\n- Elmore Leonard, Elmore Leonard's 10 Rules of Writing\n|\nWhen we live in ignorance, we live in darkness and that is where the devil rules.\n\n- Sunday Adelaja, The Mountain of Ignorance\n|\nWhere else,' I will say, 'does an old turtle crossing the path Make all the difference in the world?\n\n- Patricia MacLachlan, All the Places to Love\n|\nOh, Vasu. People always talk; you have to learn to ignore them.\n\n- Farahad Zama, Not All Marriages are Made in Heaven\n|\nAlmost all the time, you tell yourself you're loving somebody when you're just using them. This only looks like love.\n\n- Chuck Palahniuk, Invisible Monsters\n|\nAlways mystify, torture, mislead, and surprise the audience as much as possible.\n\n- Don\n|\nMen say they know many things;But lo! they have taken wings, —The arts and sciences,And a thousand appliances;The wind that blowsIs all that any body knows\n\n- Henry David Thoreau, Walden\n|\nWas not writing poetry a secret transaction, a voice answering a voice?\n\n- Virginia Woolf, Orlando\n|\nShe sat in her perfect house, with her perfect husband, wishing that her perfect life would end.\n\n- Atticus Poetry, Love Her Wild: Poems\n|\nWait. Take your foot off the pedal. Instead, let your creativity drive you.\n\n- Scott\n|\nFrom fire, water, the passage of time, neglectful readers, and the hand of the censor, each of my books has escaped to tell me its story.\n\n- Alberto Manguel, The Library at Night\n|\nIf you dare nothing, then when the day is over, nothing is all you will have gained.\n\n- Neil Gaiman, The Graveyard Book\n|\nYou see, if we have no hope, we have nothing\n\n- Tarun\n|\nWe must do our work for its own sake, not for fortune or attention or applause.\n\n- Steven Pressfield, The War of Art: Break Through 